> Just to be clear (remember, I'm still a beginner) If I select these free models, can I do a task, commit, change models, do
another task, commit, come back to you and you update the memory bank?

⏺ YES! Exactly that workflow will work perfectly.

  Here's the step-by-step:

  Your Multi-Model Workflow:

  Scenario: Claude Code (me) gets throttled mid-session

  1. Switch to Cline + Free Model:
    - Open Cline in VS Code
    - Change model to x-ai/grok-code-fast-1 or cline/code-supernova-1-million
  2. Do Task 1 with Cline:
    - Ask Cline to make changes
    - Cline edits files, runs commands
    - git add . && git commit -m "task 1"
  3. Switch Models in Cline (optional):
    - Try different free model for Task 2
    - Do another task
    - git commit -m "task 2"
  4. Come Back to Me (Claude Code):
    - Start new Claude Code session (when throttling ends)
    - I read the git history and see what Cline did
    - You tell me: "Update Memory Bank"
    - I update Memory Bank with ALL changes (mine + Cline's)

  Why This Works:

  - ✅ Git commits preserve all work (doesn't matter which AI did it)
  - ✅ Memory Bank tracks project state (not which AI was used)
  - ✅ I can see Cline's commits in git history
  - ✅ Everything stays in sync

